{"id":"1312.1563","submitter":"Svante Janson","authors":"Svante Janson","title":"On degenerate sums of $m$-dependent variables","comments":"11 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.PR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  It is well-known that the central limit theorem holds for partial sums of a\nstationary sequence $(X_i)$ of $m$-dependent random variables with finite\nvariance; however, the limit may be degenerate with variance 0 even if\n$\\mathrm{Var}(X_i)\\neq0$. We show that this happens only in the case when\n$X_i-\\mathbb E X_i=Y_i-Y_{i-1}$ for an $(m-1)$-dependent stationary sequence\n$(Y_i)$ with finite variance (a result implicit in earlier results), and give a\nversion for block factors. This yields a simple criterion that is a sufficient\ncondition for the limit not to degenerate. Two applications to subtree counts\nin random trees are given.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 5 Dec 2013 14:29:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2013-12-06"}
